  \'95 \'93System Data\'94 on macOS is a catch\uc0\u8209 all bucket (caches, logs, local snapshots, iOS backups, app support data, etc.). You generally can\'92t delete it directly, but you can reduce it safely.\
\
    Quick, safe ways to shrink it\
\
    1. Restart your Mac\
       This often purges temp files and recalculates storage.\
    2. Remove Time Machine local snapshots\
       These can get large.\
\
    - Open Terminal and run:\
      tmutil listlocalsnapshots /\
      If you see snapshots, you can delete them:\
      sudo tmutil deletelocalsnapshots <snapshot_name>\
\
    3. Clear large caches\
\
    - Finder \uc0\u8594  Go \u8594  Go to Folder\'85 \u8594  ~/Library/Caches\
      Delete contents of large app folders.\
    - Also check /Library/Caches (requires admin).\
\
    4. Find large \'93Application Support\'94 folders\
\
    - Finder \uc0\u8594  Go \u8594  Go to Folder\'85 \u8594  ~/Library/Application Support\
      Sort by size and remove old app data you no longer need.\
\
    5. Remove old iOS device backups\
\
    - Finder \uc0\u8594  your iPhone \u8594  \'93Manage Backups\'85\'94\
      Or delete from ~/Library/Application Support/MobileSync/Backup\
\
    6. Check for large log files\
\
    - Go to Folder\'85 \uc0\u8594  ~/Library/Logs and /Library/Logs\
\
    7. Use built\uc0\u8209 in Storage tools\
       System Settings \uc0\u8594  General \u8594  Storage \u8594  Review large files, downloads, unused apps.\
